Article

Molecular Mechanism of J-Domain-Triggered ATP Hydrolysis by Hsp70 Chaperones

Graphical Abstract

Authors
Roman Kityk, Ju€rgen Kopp, Matthias P. Mayer

Correspondence
m.mayer@zmbh.uni-heidelberg.de

In Brief
Kityk et al. determine the structure of the J-domain of a cochaperone in complex with Hsp70$ATP. Their work provides insights into how the J-domain and misfolded proteins collaborate to induce Hsp70 ATPase activity, allowing Hsp70 to trap the misfolded proteins.

Highlights
d We solved the crystal structure of a J-domain in complex with Hsp70$ATP
d Our structure reveals how the J-domain stimulates Hsp70’s ATPase activity
d The J-domain is linked to the catalytic ATPase center via a network of interactions
d The J-domain is linked to residues that transmit the synergistic substrate signal
Kityk et al., 2018, Molecular Cell 69, 227–237 January 18, 2018 ª 2017 Elsevier Inc. https://doi.org/10.1016/j.molcel.2017.12.003

Molecular Cell
Article

Molecular Mechanism of J-Domain-Triggered ATP Hydrolysis by Hsp70 Chaperones
Roman Kityk,1,3 Ju€rgen Kopp,2,3 and Matthias P. Mayer1,4,* 1Center for Molecular Biology of Heidelberg University (ZMBH), DKFZ-ZMBH Alliance, 69120 Heidelberg, Germany 2Biochemistry Center of Heidelberg University (BZH), 69120 Heidelberg, Germany 3These authors contributed equally 4Lead Contact *Correspondence: m.mayer@zmbh.uni-heidelberg.de https://doi.org/10.1016/j.molcel.2017.12.003

SUMMARY
Efﬁcient targeting of Hsp70 chaperones to substrate proteins depends on J-domain cochaperones, which in synergism with substrates trigger ATP hydrolysis in Hsp70s and concomitant substrate trapping. We present the crystal structure of the J-domain of Escherichia coli DnaJ in complex with the E. coli Hsp70 DnaK. The J-domain interacts not only with DnaK’s nucleotide-binding domain (NBD) but also with its substrate-binding domain (SBD) and packs against the highly conserved interdomain linker. Mutational replacement of contacts between J-domain and SBD strongly reduces the ability of substrates to stimulate ATP hydrolysis in the presence of DnaJ and compromises viability at heat shock temperatures. Our data demonstrate that the J-domain and the substrate do not deliver completely independent signals for ATP hydrolysis, but the J-domain, in addition to its direct inﬂuence on Hsp70s catalytic center, makes Hsp70 more responsive for the hydrolysis-inducing signal of the substrate, resulting in efﬁcient substrate trapping.
INTRODUCTION
The 70-kDa heat shock proteins (Hsp70s) constitute the central hub of the cellular protein quality surveillance network, assisting numerous protein-folding processes and cooperating with all major cellular chaperone systems (Mayer and Bukau, 2005). Processes involving Hsp70s include folding of newly synthesized polypeptides and their trafﬁcking across membranes; prevention of protein aggregation, solubilization of protein aggregates, and their subsequent refolding; assembly and disassembly of oligomeric protein structures; control of activity of many regulatory proteins; and protein degradation by the proteasome and autophagy (Kettern et al., 2010; Meimaridou et al., 2009). Not surprisingly, Hsp70s are linked to numerous diseases, notably cancer, neurodegeneration, and infections (Calderwood et al., 2006; Fontaine et al., 2016; Ghazaei, 2017; Mayer, 2005; Radons,

2016; Shonhai et al., 2011), and in recent years became a target for drug development (Zuiderweg et al., 2017).
The enormous versatility of Hsp70 chaperones relies on the transient interaction of their C-terminal substrate polypeptidebinding domain (SBD) with a short degenerative sequence motif found frequently in virtually all proteins (Ru€diger et al., 1997). This interaction is regulated through an intricate allosteric mechanism between their N-terminal nucleotide-binding domain (NBD) and their SBD, resulting in ultrahigh afﬁnity through a non-equilibrium binding mode (De Los Rios and Barducci, 2014; Mayer and Kityk, 2015; Zuiderweg et al., 2013). In the ATP-bound state, afﬁnity for polypeptides is low but peptide association and dissociation rates are high. Upon ATP hydrolysis, afﬁnity of polypeptides is increased 10- to 50-fold, while peptide association and dissociation rates are decreased 100- and more than 1,000-fold, respectively (Figure 1A). The structures of the ATP- and ADPbound conformations rationalized these differences (Figure 1B). Ultrahigh afﬁnity is achieved when polypeptides associate with high rates to the ATP-bound state and concomitant ATP hydrolysis traps the substrate protein by transition to the ADP-bound state with low substrate dissociation rates. However, the intrinsic ATP hydrolysis rate of Hsp70 is very low and requires timely stimulation by the substrate itself in synergism with J-domain proteins (JDPs) (Karzai and McMacken, 1996; Laufen et al., 1999). Although Hsp70s are paradigm chaperones, in the absence of JDPs, they generally fail in the most basic chaperone function: the prevention of protein aggregation. Thus, efﬁcient interaction of Hsp70s with substrates depends entirely on JDP co-chaperones, which act as targeting factors for Hsp70s.
The number of JDPs present in each cell has increased tremendously in the course of evolution (Kampinga and Craig, 2010). JDPs are multi-domain proteins that are divided in three classes according to their domain composition. All JDPs contain the name-giving J-domain, a helical hairpin structure of 70–75 residues, which is at the N terminus of class A and class B JDPs but can be anywhere in class C proteins. Class A JDPs share all domains of the prototypic Escherichia coli DnaJ: the N-terminal J-domain is followed by a glycine/phenylalanine (G/F)-rich ﬂexible region of $30 residues, two homologous b sandwich domains, with a Zn2+-ﬁnger domain inserted into the ﬁrst of the two, and a C-terminal dimerization domain. Class B JDPs contain all domains of class A proteins except for the Zn2+ ﬁnger. Class C JDPs only have the J-domain in common and can have a wide variety of other domains or functional

Molecular Cell 69, 227–237, January 18, 2018 ª 2017 Elsevier Inc. 227

