Figure 1. Crystal Structure of DnaK$ATP in Complex with the J-Domain of DnaJ (A) JDPs in synergism with substrates stimulate the ATPase activity of Hsp70 proteins, leading to efﬁcient substrate trapping. (B) Structure of Hsp70$ATP (PDB: 4B9Q) and Hsp70$ADP (PDB: 2KHO) with bound substrate (dark blue spheres). (C) Structure of DnaK in complex with ATP$Mg2+ and the J-domain of DnaJ. NBD in dark teal (lobe I) and cyan (lobe II), linker in yellow, SBDb in dark red, SBDa in orange, the J-domain in purple (PDB: 5NRO), and the HPD motif in green spheres.

motifs. Class A and class B JDPs are considered general cochaperones that interact with unfolded, misfolded, or aggregated proteins and transfer them to Hsp70. Class C proteins are believed to be more speciﬁc for a small subset of substrates or are located at places like the ribosomal exit tunnel or translocation pores where polypeptides emerge to be bound by Hsp70. Genetic and biochemical data demonstrated that the J-domain is necessary and sufﬁcient for functional interaction with Hsp70s (Karzai and McMacken, 1996; Wall et al., 1994). Therefore, the J-domain-Hsp70 interaction is at the heart of the multitude of functions of Hsp70 systems.
Here, we present the crystal structure of the J-domain of E. coli DnaJ in complex with the ATP-bound open conformation of the E. coli Hsp70 DnaK. Our structure reveals the molecular mechanism for the synergistic action of J-domain and substrate in stimulating the ATPase activity of Hsp70 and trapping substrates.
RESULTS
Overcoming the Constrains of Transient J-DomainHsp70 Interactions To overcome the main obstacle to structural investigations of the J-domain-Hsp70 interaction, the transient nature of this interaction, we fused the ﬁrst 105 amino acids of DnaJ, comprising the J-domain and the G/F-rich region, via a three-residue linker to the N terminus of DnaK (further referred to as JD-DnaK) (Figure S1A). The unstructured 33-residue G/F-rich region (Szyperski et al., 1994) bridges more than 100 A˚ and allows the J-domain to reach any position in DnaK, since in the ATP-bound conformation, no part of DnaK is more than 60 A˚ away from its N terminus (Kityk et al., 2012). Furthermore, the J-domain and G/F-rich region are sufﬁcient to replace full-length DnaJ and its close homolog, CbpA, in E. coli, allowing the DdnaJ DcbpA strain to grow at 14.5C and 39.5C (Kelley and Georgopoulos, 1997), downregulate the heat shock response (Wall et al., 1995), and support

bacteriophage l replication (Wall et al., 1994). The J-domain in the chimeric protein stimulated ATPase activity 20 times more efﬁciently than equimolar concentrations of DnaJ(1–105) stimulate DnaKwt when added in trans, consistent with the expectation that the fusion construct provides J-domain function at a much higher local concentration (Figures S1B and S1C). Thus, the J-domain of JD-DnaK functionally interacts with the Hsp70 part of the fusion construct. Of note, full-length DnaJ, added at the high concentrations used in our quenchedﬂow single-turnover ATPase assays (10 mM), was able to stimulate DnaKwt to ATPase rates similar to those as observed for our JDDnaK construct. Because full-length DnaJ is known to mimic a substrate in the absence of other protein substrates, thereby providing the J-domain and a substrate signal for ATP hydrolysis (Laufen et al., 1999), our construct also might provide J-domain and substrate function, presumably through the G/F-rich linker. For crystallization, we introduced three additional modiﬁcations into JD-DnaK to stabilize the ATP state of the protein. First, we replaced Thr199 (DnaK numbering throughout) with alanine, which abrogates ATPase activity without affecting the allosteric mechanism (Barthel et al., 2001) (Figure S1A). Second, we covalently ﬁxed the a-helical lid of the SBD (SBDa) to the NBD via a disulﬁde bridge formed between cysteines introduced at positions 47 and 529, which stabilizes the physiologically relevant open conformation of DnaK (Kityk et al., 2012). Third, we replaced the last 30 residues of DnaK, known to be unstructured (Zhu et al., 1996), by 5 histidine residues. This construct, DnaJ(1–105)-DnaK(2–606)E47C,T199A,F529C-H5 (short JD-DnaKcryst), was oxidized to form a disulﬁde bridge and crystallized.
Overall Structure of the J-Domain-DnaK Complex Phases were obtained by molecular replacement using the structure of full-length DnaK (Kityk et al., 2012), residues 3–65 of the J-domain were built manually, and the complex reﬁned at 3.25 A˚ resolution (Table 1). The J-domain (3–65) and DnaK (2–604) are well deﬁned in the electron density, whereas no electron density was observed for the G/F region (Figures 1C and S1D). The structure of DnaK in the JD-DnaKcryst construct closely resembles the structure of DnaK$ATP solved previously (Kityk et al., 2012; Qi et al., 2013) with small changes close to the bound J-domain (Figures 2A and 2B). The DnaK part consists of the

