NBD in complex with Mg2+-ATP and the SBD in the open conformation with a-helical lid (SBDa) and b sandwich domain (SBDb) separated from each other and docked onto the NBD. The highly conserved interdomain linker, which is important for ATP hydrolysis (Vogel et al., 2006b), is inserted into the lower crevice of the NBD. The J-domain consists of four a helices (I–IV) and is similar to the nuclear magnetic resonance (NMR) structures of DnaJ’s J-domain (Figure 2C). The J-domain binds to DnaK at the interface formed between NBD and SBDb (Figure 1C), and contacts formed between J-domain and DnaK, covering an interface area of 923 A˚ 2, are fully consistent with genetic, biochemical, and structural data available (Figures 2D and 2E), including a recent molecular modeling study (Malinverni et al., 2017).
Interactions of the J-Domain with the NBD and the Universally Conserved Linker The universally conserved HPD motif (His33-Pro34-Asp35), which is essential for stimulation of the ATPase activity in all

J-domain/Hsp70 pairs tested so far (Campbell et al., 1997; Kelley and Georgopoulos, 1997; Tsai and Douglas, 1996; Wall
et al., 1994), protrudes toward the interdomain linker of DnaK (Figure 1C). His33JD, Tyr25JD, and Met30JD form hydrophobic contacts with the linker residues Leu390DnaK and Leu392DnaK (Figure 3A). In addition, His33JD/NE2 is at hydrogen-bond distance to the backbone carbonyl of Leu391DnaK, Arg36JD/NH1 and NH2 form polar contacts with the backbone carbonyls of Lys387DnaK and Val389DnaK (Figure 3B), and Asp35JD/OD2 interacts with Arg167DnaK/NH1. Notably, Arg167DnaK, Leu390DnaK, and Leu392DnaK were previously suggested to be involved in DnaK-DnaJ interactions and Leu391DnaK in allostery in DnaK
(Kumar et al., 2011; Laufen et al., 1999; Mayer et al., 1999; Suh et al., 1998), and Tyr25JD and Arg36JD are important for DnaJ function in vivo (Genevaux et al., 2002). Additionally, Asp35JD/OD2 interacts with Gln378DnaK/NE2 in the NBD. Gln378 had not been implicated in DnaK-DnaJ interactions before. Thus, we replaced Gln378DnaK with alanine and determined the efﬁciency of DnaJ and a substrate to stimulate the
ATPase activity of the mutant protein. At the concentrations employed, the low basal ATPase rate of DnaKwt (0.0007 sÀ1) was stimulated 11.7-fold by DnaJ, 3.7-fold by the physiological substrate heat shock transcription factor s32, and 23-fold in the presence of both (Figure 3C). The basal ATPase activity of DnaK-Q378A was stimulated 2.9-fold by s32 but only 3-fold by
DnaJ and 5-fold when both co-factors were added, suggesting that Gln378DnaK is important for the interaction with DnaJ. Moreover, DnaK-Q378A was less efﬁcient than DnaKwt in refolding
chemically denatured luciferase in vitro (Figure 3D) and supported growth of a DdnaK strain at 40C less well when expressed a equal levels (Figures 3E and S2), suggesting that Gln378DnaK is important for DnaK’s chaperone activity in vitro
and in vivo.
Interactions of the J-Domain with the SBD Coordinates
Substrate Signal
Two polar/electrostatic and hydrophobic contact interfaces between the J-domain and DnaK ensure correct positioning of the J-domain at the NBD-SBD interface of DnaK (Figure S3). The ﬁrst interface is formed between helix II of the J-domain and lobe II of the NBD, involving Arg22JD/NH2-Glu206DnaK/OE1, Arg22JD/NH2-Glu217DnaK/OE1, Lys26JD/NZ-Glu217DnaK/OE1, and Arg27JD/NH2-Asp211DnaK/OD2 (Figure 4A). These residues
were implicated previously in DnaK-DnaJ interactions (Ahmad et al., 2011; Ga€ssler et al., 1998). The second contact interface is formed between the HPD motif and helix III of the J-domain and the SBDb of DnaK. This interface involves two polar contacts, Lys48JD/NZ-Asp477DnaK/OD1 and Lys51JD/NZ-Thr420DnaK/ OG1, and two hydrophobic contacts, Pro34JD-Pro419DnaK and Phe47JD-Pro419DnaK (Figures 3A, 3B, and 4B). To our knowledge, such an interaction has never been suggested before. However, Pro34JD and Phe47JD were shown to be important in vivo (Genevaux et al., 2002), and replacement of Pro419DnaK inﬂu-
ences substrate binding (Burkholder et al., 1996). We analyzed the importance of the remaining contacts for DnaK functions in vivo. In contrast to DnaK-T420A, DnaK-D477A was not able
to complement the temperature-sensitivity phenotype of the DdnaK strain when expressed at equal levels (Figures 4C and

