S2). Consistently, a DdnaJ DcbpA strain harboring DnaJ-K48A or DnaJ-K48E exhibited growth defects at 40C (Figure S4A). These data suggest that the Asp477DnaK-Lys48JD contact, but not the Thr420DnaK-Lys51JD contact, is critical for the DnaK-DnaJ system in vivo. Of note, Lys51JD/NZ may also form contacts with Glu55JD/OE1 and OE2, which may weaken the Thr420DnaKLys51JD contact, suggesting a reason why its contribution to
the J-domain/DnaK interaction is small. However, the mutant
J-domain (DnaJ(1–75)-K51A) stimulated ATPase activity of wild-
type DnaK in synergism with a substrate peptide, comprising the DnaK recognition sequence within s32 (Rodriguez et al.,
2008), less efﬁciently than the wild-type J-domain of DnaJ (Figure S4B), suggesting that Lys51JD nevertheless contributes to
the interaction with DnaK. In contrast, DnaJ(1–75)-K48A did not
signiﬁcantly stimulate ATPase activity under these conditions
compared with stimulation of the peptide alone, indicating that

the Lys48JD-Asp477DnaK interaction is much more important. Similarly, the replacement of Lys26 and Arg36 of DnaJ(1–75), two other sites with polar contacts with DnaK (see above), with alanine also compromised J-domain function in single-turnover ATPase assays, indicating that these contacts are also much more important for the J-domain DnaK interaction than the Lys51JD-Thr420DnaK interaction (Figure S4B).
In vitro, DnaK-D477A refolded chemically denatured luciferase less efﬁciently than DnaKwt (Figure 4D). Individually, DnaJ and s32 stimulated the ATPase activity of DnaK-D477A only 1.7-fold and together 5.3-fold, which is signiﬁcantly lower than the stimulation of DnaKwt (Figure 4E). The decreased stimulation of DnaK-D477A’s ATPase activity by s32 relative to DnaKwt was unexpected, because Asp477 is more than 15 A˚ away from the substrate-binding cleft. Indeed, afﬁnity measurements revealed that DnaK-D477A has a 2.3-fold lower afﬁnity for the substrate

