than DnaKwt (Figure 4F). However, the reduced afﬁnity of DnaKD477A for substrates was not responsible for the reduced synergistic stimulation of its ATPase activity. We compared the ATPase activity of DnaK-D477A in the presence of 20 nM DnaJ and increasing concentrations of s32 with the ATPase activity of DnaKwt and DnaK-M404A, a DnaK variant with an afﬁnity for substrates comparable to DnaK-D477A (Mayer et al., 2000). Despite a 2.8-fold lower afﬁnity for substrates, DnaK-M404A’s ATPase activity was as responsive to stimulation with increasing concentrations of s32 in the presence of DnaJ as DnaKwt’s ATPase activity (Figure 4G). In contrast, the ATPase activity of DnaK-D477A was stimulated much less efﬁciently, suggesting that Asp477 is indeed required for efﬁcient synergistic stimulation of ATPase activity by DnaJ and a substrate.
The backbone amide and carbonyl of Asp477 form hydrogen bonds with the amide and carbonyl of His485, which is contiguous to Leu484, a residue previously demonstrated to be an essential part of the signal transduction pathway from the substrate to the catalytic center for ATP hydrolysis (Kityk et al., 2015). Consistently, increasing concentrations of s32 also stimulated the ATP hydrolysis rate of DnaKwt less efﬁciently in the presence of DnaJ-K48A than in the presence of DnaJwt, demonstrating that disruption of the Lys48JD-Asp477DnaK interaction handicaps signal transduction from the substrate to the catalytic center in DnaKwt.
Residues Involved in the J-domain-Hsp70 Interaction Are Evolutionarily Conserved To answer the question whether the J-domain-Hsp70 interface is conserved in evolution we performed blast searches in

combination with multiple sequence alignments. We used E. coli DnaJ, Saccharomyces cerevisiae Ydj1, and human DnaJA1 (Hdj2), as examples for class A JDPs, E. coli CbpA, S. cerevisiae Sis1, and human DnaJB1 (Hdj1) as examples of class B JDPs in a BLAST query against the UNIPROT90 (DnaJ, Ydj1, CbpA, and Sis1) database of clusters of 90% mutually identical protein sequences or against the database of vertebrate protein sequences (DnaJA1 and DnaJB1) on the European Molecular Biology Laboratory (EMBL) EBI server. We retrieved 200 sequences for each query and performed a Clustal U alignment. After removal of incomplete sequences, we retained 200 (DnaJ), 198 (Ydj1), 187 (DnaJA1), 189 (CbpA), 200 (Sis1), and 183 (DnaJB1) sequences and analyzed the conservation of the residues indicated. Except for Lys51JD, which is not essential, all sites involved in the interaction of the J-domain with DnaK are conserved in JDPs from bacteria to humans (Figure 5, top). Similarly, the sequences of E. coli DnaK, S. cerevisiae Ssa1, and human Hsc70 were used as query against the UNIPROT90 and vertebrate database and the retrieved sequences (200 each) used in Clustal U alignments (Figure 5A, bottom). These alignments suggest that all J-domains interact with Hsp70s in a similar way. To test this hypothesis, we replaced Glu218, Gln376, and Asp479 in human Hsc70 (corresponding to Glu217, Gln378, and Asp477 in E. coli DnaK) with alanine and determined the single-turnover ATPase rates of wild-type and mutant proteins in the absence and presence of the human JDP Hdj1 (Figure 5B). Whereas the replacement of these residues in human Hsc70 did not affect basal ATPase activity, stimulation of ATPase activity by Hdj1 was signiﬁcantly lower, demonstrating that these residues are also important for functional interaction of the J-domain of human Hdj1 with human Hsc70.

