In addition, we performed an alignment using all Hsp70 sequences found in the genomes of E. coli, S. cerevisiae, and Homo sapiens, including the more distant relatives. Most sites in DnaK contacted by the J-domain are conserved in canonical Hsp70 proteins, but not in Hsp70 homologs that do not interact with JDPs, as the Hsp110s and Hsp70 components of the ribosome-associated complex (Figure S5). We also performed a similar alignment of all JDPs of E. coli, S. cerevisiae, and the class A and class B JDPs of humans. These alignments show some deviations between paralogs within the same organism (Figure S5), possibly tuning the interaction within the JDP network or allowing for specialized Hsp70-JDP pairs (Kluck et al., 2002; Pukszta et al., 2010; Schlenstedt et al., 1995; Silberg et al., 1998).
DISCUSSION
The structure we present of the J-domain in complex with Hsp70 in the ATP-bound open conformation explains a host of genetic, biochemical, and biophysical data. It conﬁrms previously proposed contacts of the J-domain with Hsp70’s NBD and interdomain linker, reveals previously unsuspected but mechanistically important interactions between the J-domain and the SBDb of Hsp70, and assigns a functional role for the universally

conserved HPD motif of the J-domain and the interdomain linker in Hsp70s. Our structure provides the basis for understanding how JDPs in synergism with substrate proteins stimulate ATP hydrolysis in Hsp70s and thus enables Hsp70s to rapidly trap misfolded proteins. Since the discovery that the paradigm JDP DnaJ stimulates the ATPase activity of DnaK (Liberek et al., 1991), many attempts have been made to solve the molecular mechanism of this interaction (Ahmad et al., 2011; Ga€ssler et al., 1998; Genevaux et al., 2002; Greene et al., 1998; Kumar et al., 2011; Smock et al., 2010; Suh et al., 1998, 1999). Residues identiﬁed in these studies to be affected by interaction are in close proximity in our structure, and residues found to be functionally important are either at the interface between the J-domain and Hsp70 or on the pathway to the catalytic ATPase center (Figure 2). The most recent attempt to derive a model for the J-domain-Hsp70 interaction used a combination of coarse-grain and atomistic models and evolutionary sequence analysis (Malinverni et al., 2017). The coevolutionary analysis in this study predicted three interaction pairs: Asn187DnaK-Lys23JD, Asp208DnaK-Lys26JD, and Thr189DnaKArg19JD. However, these residues do not form contacts in our structure. In fact, they are $10, 6, and 16 A˚ apart from each other, respectively. These residues might be important for initial contacts of the J-domain with DnaK, before attaining the ﬁnal position. Alternatively, coevolution of these residues may have different reasons. In addition, interactions between

