panel, except that the sequences of E. coli DnaK,

S. cerevisiae Ssa1, and human Hsc70 were used

as a query. The arrows between the two panels

connect the pairs of residues that interact with

each other. The brackets indicate polar interaction

with the backbone carbonyl or amide proton. Of

note, because of a short (4-residue) deletion in

eukaryotic Hsp70s corresponding to residues

211–214 of DnaK, the Clustal U sequence align-

ment does not detect homologs of residues 206

and 211, which in our structure interact with Arg22JD and Arg27JD.

(B) Single-turnover ATPase rates of wild-type and

mutant human Hsc70 (HSPA8) in the absence and

B

presence of human Hdj1 (DNAJB1, 2 mM) (mean ±

SD, n = 3; ****p < 0.0001; ***p = 0.0001, ANOVA

Sidak’s multiple comparisons test).

His422DnaK-Glu75JD and Gln424DnaK-Lys51JD were proposed. Glu75JD is not resolved in our structure. The distance between Gln424DnaK and Lys51JD is 14 A˚ in our structure, precluding interaction. Our mutagenesis data suggest that Lys51JD is not important for the DnaK-DnaJ interaction. Moreover, a Gln424to-cysteine replacement had no functional defects in vitro and in vivo and allowed DnaJ and ATP-dependent crosslinking of the protein substrate s32 to DnaK using a benzophenone crosslinker speciﬁcally attached to this cysteine in position 424 (Laufen et al., 1999). A possible explanation why coevolution analysis failed to reveal the pairs of residues interacting in our structure could be that these residues are highly conserved from bacteria to humans, and the number of deviations may be too small to yield a statistically signiﬁcant coupling.
It could be argued that by tethering the J-domain to the N terminus of DnaK, a nonphysiological interaction was forced. However, our functional characterization of the fusion construct (Figure S1) and our mutational analysis of DnaK (Figures 3 and 4) and J-domain (Figure S4) single-amino-acid replacement variants strongly argue that our structure represents the physiologically relevant interaction.

Our structure is in conﬂict with the crystal structure of the J-domain of auxilin in complex with the NBD of bovine Hsc70 (Jiang et al., 2007). Based on a genetic study (Suh et al., 1998), which suggested a direct interaction between Asp35 of DnaJ’s HPD motif and Arg167 in DnaK, Jiang and colleagues replaced Asp876 of the HPD motif in the J-domain of auxilin and Arg171 (corresponding to Arg167 of DnaK) in the NBD of Hsc70 with cysteines and tethered the J-domain to the NBD by a disulﬁde bridge. However, this structure could not provide a mechanism of J-domain function. As compared to our structure, the J-domain points in a diametrically opposite direction (Figure S6). The only commonality between our structure and the structure of Jiang et al. is the fact that the two residues used to introduce a disulﬁde bridge indeed interact with each other. However, an aspartatearginine interaction bridges $8 A˚ between the Ca atoms of the two residues, whereas the distance between the Ca atoms of a disulﬁde bridge is only $5 A˚ . This might be the reason why steric constraints prevented the J-domain to dock onto its natural docking site. Furthermore, the SBD of the Hsp70 was missing in the previous structure. In our structure, the J-domain interacts with the SBD as well as part of the mechanism of J-domain-substrate synergism, as demonstrated by us. The high conservation of interacting residues (Figure 5A) suggests that throughout evolution, J-domains dock onto Hsp70s in a very similar way and that the molecular mechanism of the J-domain-triggered ATP hydrolysis by Hsp70s is conserved as well.

Molecular Cell 69, 227–237, January 18, 2018 233

A

Figure 6. Model for the Synergistic Stimula-

tion of the ATPase Activity of DnaK by DnaJ

and Substrate as Basis for Efﬁcient Trap-

ping of Substrates by Hsp70 Chaperones

(A) After ATP binding, the SBDb docks onto the

rotated lobes of the NBD by interaction between

Lys414 and Asp329 and between Asp481 with

Arg167 and Ile168, preventing back rotation to an

optimal position for ATP hydrolysis. In the absence

of substrate and a J-domain, basal ATPase activity

is very low (path 1). Mutating Lys414 or Asp481

increases ATPase activity by 25- to 80-fold (Kityk

et al., 2015). The addition of substrate (path 2) leads

to dissociation of the SBDb from the NBD through a

signal propagated through the SBDb to the NBD

(hatched arrows) (Zhuravleva et al., 2012), stimu-

lating ATPase activity, albeit by only 2- to 5-fold due

to complete release of the SBDb, which allows too

much freedom to the lobes of the NBD (green

arrows) and dissociation of the linker from the

lower crevice (blue arrow). The inefﬁcient stimula-

tion of ATPase activity traps substrates inefﬁciently

(transparent blue substrate symbol on DnaK), and

B

C

some substrates may dissociate before closure of

the substrate-binding pocket (arrow with trans-

parent blue substrate symbol). In the simultaneous

presence of DnaJ and a substrate (path 3), the

J-domain binds at the interface between SBDb and

NBD, stimulates ATPase activity directly through

the interaction network from the linker to the cata-

lytic center and indirectly by making DnaK more

sensitive to the substrate signal (solid arrows in the

SBDb), and prevents dissociation of SBDb and

linker, leading to a very high ATPase rate and

effective trapping of the substrate.

(B) Structure of the DnaK-J-domain complex

highlighting as spheres His33 and Asp35 of the

J-domain, residues involved in SBDb docking onto

the NBD, and residues involved in signal transmission from the substrate to the NBD (Val440, Leu484, and Asp148; Kityk et al., 2015).

(C) Schematic representation of the network of polar and non-polar contacts connecting the J-domain to the catalytic center of the NBD. Arrows indicate polar

contacts, and hatched lines non-polar contacts.

See also Movie S2.

This hypothesis is supported by a mutational study using the J-domain of polyomavirus large T-antigen (Whalen et al., 2005). These authors identiﬁed several residues which compromise T antigen function in vivo and stimulation of the ATPase activity of Hsc70 in vitro. In a homology model of polyomavirus J-domain onto the J-domain of DnaJ in our structure and of human Hsc70 on DnaK in our structure, 5 of the 6 identiﬁed T-antigen residues would be within interaction distance to Hsc70, requiring only minor adjustments by rotation around single bonds. The remaining amino acid replacements (A33G) in T antigen would be expected to destabilize the J-domain, since in our model, it forms hydrophobic interaction with Leu19 of the J-domain. In addition, Ala33 is in the middle of helix II, and replacement by glycine is expected to break the helix. Thus, our structure is also consistent with a mutagenesis analysis of polyomavirus large T antigen in mammalian cells, suggesting conservation of the mechanistic principal of J-domain-Hsp70 interaction. Moreover, overlaying the J-domain of auxilin on the J-domain of DnaJ and homology modeling human Hsc70 onto DnaK reveals that auxilin could interact

with Hsc70 in a way similar to that of the J-domain of DnaJ with DnaK. In fact, mutations used by Jiang and colleagues to support their structure would also affect interaction in such a model. Our single-turnover ATPase data of human Hsc70 in the presence of the human JDP Hdj1 (Figure 5) support our claim that the interaction between the J-domain of DnaJ and DnaK revealed by our structure is evolutionarily conserved.
Our J-domain-DnaK structure allows us to propose a molecular mechanism of how JDPs trigger ATP hydrolysis of Hsp70 chaperones (Figure 6). Hsp70s possess very low basal ATPase activity, because ATP binding rotates the two lobes of the NBD into a position incompatible with g-phosphate cleavage and SBDb docking prevents back rotation of the NBD lobes (Kityk et al., 2012, 2015). Substrate binding perturbs the NBD-SBDb interface of Hsp70, releasing the structural constraints of the NBD, as suggested by NMR data (Zhuravleva et al., 2012), but increases the ATPase activity only moderately, since the catalytic residues often bypass the optimal position for hydrolysis due to the high rotational freedom of the NBD lobes. Full stimulation of ATPase activity is achieved

234 Molecular Cell 69, 227–237, January 18, 2018

in the presence of both substrate and J-domain. The J-domain makes signal transmission from the substrate-binding cleft to the NBD more efﬁcient and thus favors substrate-induced destabilization of the NBD-SBDb interface and initiation of the back rotation of the NBD lobes (Figure 6B). Concomitantly, substrate-induced conformational changes in the SBDb are transmitted to the J-domain (Figure S7; Movie S1), leading through the contacts of the HPD motif to a readjustment of the linker in the NBD crevice, and thereby arrest the NBD lobes and catalytic residues in a position optimal for ATP hydrolysis. In addition, the HPD motif accesses a hydrogen bond network that ends at the catalytic Glu171DnaK and Lys70DnaK (Figure 6C; Movie S2). Thus, the J-domain couples two signals to trigger ATP hydrolysis with concomitant trapping of the substrate. In this way, the Hsp70-JDP machinery achieves ultrahigh afﬁnity, with a non-equilibrium KD that is 2 to 3 orders of magnitude lower than that of the high-afﬁnity ADP-bound equilibrium state (De Los Rios and Barducci, 2014), and the high association rates necessary to efﬁciently compete with protein aggregation.
