CONTACT FOR REAGENT AND RESOURCE SHARING
Further information and requests for resources and reagents should be directed to and will be fulﬁlled by the Lead Contact, Matthias P. Mayer (m.mayer@zmbh.uni-heidelberg.de)
EXPERIMENTAL MODEL AND SUBJECT DETAILS
For in vivo complementation assays E. coli BB1994 (DdnaK52 strain BB1553; Bukau and Walker, 1990; + lacIq plasmid pDM1.1; Lanzer and Bujard, 1988) or E. coli WKG190 (DdnaJ DcbpA strain; Kelley and Georgopoulos, 1997) were used.
METHOD DETAILS
Plasmid construction For the construction of an expression plasmid for JD-DnaK and JD-DnaKcryst the coding sequence of DnaJ(1-105) was ampliﬁed by polymerase chain reaction (PCR) using primer JD_5 and JD-GF_3 (Table S1) and cloned into the EcoRI and BglII restriction sites of the arabinose-inducible expression plasmids pMPM-A4 (Mayer, 1995) containing the coding sequences for DnaKwt and DnaK(1-606)-E47C,T199A,F529C-His5 (Kityk et al., 2012). The dnaK genes in the resulting plasmids were completed by amplifying the dnaK sequence using primers dnaK-NdeI_5 and dnaK_936- (Table S1) and the plasmids pMPM-A4-dnaKwt and pMPM-A4-dnaK(1-606)-E47C,T199A,F529C-His5 as templates and insertion into the NdeI and BglII restriction sites. The expression plasmids for DnaJ(1-75) and DnaJ(1-105) were constructed by PCR ampliﬁcation of the respective dnaJ sequences using primers dnaJ_5, dnaJ(1-75)_3 and dnaJ(1-105)_3 and a wild-type dnaJ containing plasmid as template and insertion into the vector pMPM-A4-EcSUMO. Expression plasmids for mutant proteins were constructed by site directed mutagenesis (Kunkel et al., 1991) using the oligonucleotides listed in Table S1. DnaJ(1-75)-K26A was constructed by inserting the annealed primers K26A_s and K26A_as into the BlpI and RsrII restriction sites of pMPM-A4-EcSUMO-dnaJ(1-75). For complementation of the DdnaJ DcbpA strain WGK190 the coding sequences for DnaJwt and mutant proteins were cloned into pMPM-A6 (Mayer, 1995). For the complementation of the DdnaK52 strain mutant dnaK genes were cloned into pUHE21-2fdD12 (Buchberger et al., 1994). The coding sequences of all constructs were completely sequenced.
Protein puriﬁcation Puriﬁcation of JD-DnaK fusion proteins, DnaKwt and its variants – JD-DnaK fusion proteins, DnaKwt and its mutant variants were puriﬁed as native proteins with an N-terminal His-SUMO tag (DnaK variants) or a C-terminal His-tag (JD-DnaK fusion proteins) after overproduction in DdnaK52 cells (BB1553; Bukau and Walker, 1990). Cell pellets were resuspended in lysis buffer (20 mM Tris/HCl pH 7.9, 100 mM KCl, 1 mM PMSF), subjected to lysis by Microﬂuidizer Emulsi Flex C5 (Avestin, Ottawa, Canada), and afterward applied onto a column with Ni-IDA resin (Macherey-Nagel, Du€ren, Germany). The column was washed with 20 column volumes of lysis buffer and 10 column volumes of ATP buffer (20 mM Tris/HCl pH 7.9, 100 mM KCl, 5 mM MgCl2, 5 mM ATP), and proteins were eluted with elution buffer (20mM Tris/HCl pH 7.9, 100 mM KCl, 250 mM imidazol). In the case of His-SUMO-fused variants, the proteins were treated with Ulp1 protease to remove the His-SUMO tag from DnaK. Subsequently, the protein mixture was subjected again to a Ni-IDA column and the ﬂow-through fraction containing tag-free DnaK was collected. Nucleotides bound to DnaK were removed by treating the samples with calf intestine alkaline phosphatase (AP; 2U AP per mg DnaK) at room temperature overnight during dialysis into the nucleotide removal buffer (50mM Tris/HCL, pH 7.5, 100 mM KCl, 2 mM EDTA, 2 mM NaN3, 2 mM b-mercaptoethanol, 10% glycerol). To remove alkaline phosphatase, DnaK was loaded onto an anion exchange column (Resource Q, GE Healthcare), equilibrated in low salt buffer (40 mM HEPES/KOH pH 7.6, 100 mM KCl, 5 MgCl2), and eluted with a linear KCl gradient (0.1–1 M) of 10 column volumes (CV).
Puriﬁcation of DnaJwt and DnaJ-K48A – DnaJwt and DnaJ-K48A were puriﬁed as native proteins after overproduction in DdnaJ DcbpA E. coli cells (WKG190; Kelley and Georgopoulos, 1997). Cell pellets were resuspended in lysis buffer (50 mM Tris/HCl pH 8, 10 mM DTT, 0.6% (w/v) Brij 58, 1 mM PMSF, 0.8 mg/ml Lysozyme) and lysed by Microﬂuidizer Emulsi Flex C5. Cell debris was removed by centrifugation at 15,000 rpm for 30 min and 1 volume of buffer A (50 mM sodium phosphate buffer pH 7, 5 mM DTT,
Molecular Cell 69, 227–237.e1–e4, January 18, 2018 e2

1 mM EDTA, 0.1% (w/v) Brij 58) was added to the supernatant. DnaJ was precipitated by addition of (NH4)2SO4 to a ﬁnal concentration of 65% (w/v) and the precipitate pelleted by centrifugation (15,000 rpm, 30 min). The ammonium sulfate pellet was dissolved in 220 mL buffer B (50 mM sodium phosphate buffer pH 7, 5 mM DTT, 1 mM EDTA, 0.1% (w/v) Brij 58, 2 M Urea) and dialyzed against 5 L buffer B. DnaJ was loaded onto a cation exchange column (SP-Sepharose, equilibrated with buffer B), washed with buffer B and eluted with a linear gradient of 0 to 666 mM KCl (15 CV). DnaJ containing fractions were pooled and dialyzed against 5 L buffer C (50 mM Tris/HCl, pH 7.5, 2 M Urea, 0.1% (w/v) Brij 58, 5 mM DTT, 50 mM KCl) and the sample was loaded onto a hydroxyapatite column equilibrated in buffer C. The column was ﬁrst washed with 1 column volume (CV) buffer C supplemented with 1 M KCl, and then with 2 CV of buffer C. DnaJ was eluted with a linear gradient (0%–50%, 1 CV) of buffer D (50 mM Tris/HCl, pH 7.5, 2 M Urea, 0.1% (w/v) Brij 58, 5 mM DTT, 50 mM KCl, 600 mM KH2PO4) and 2 CV mL of 50% buffer D. The DnaJ containing fractions were pooled and dialyzed against 2 L buffer E (50 mM Tris/HCl, pH 7.7, 100 mM KCl).
DnaJ(1-105) and DnaJ(1-75) and variants were expressed in pMPM-A4 (Mayer, 1995) and puriﬁed as native proteins with an N-terminal His-SUMO tag. Cell pellets were resuspended in lysis buffer (20 mM Tris/HCl pH 7.9, 100 mM KCl, 1 mM PMSF), subjected to lysis by Microﬂuidizer Emulsi Flex C5 (Avestin, Ottawa, Canada), and afterward applied onto a column with Ni-IDA resin (Macherey-Nagel, Du€ren, Germany). The column was washed with 20 column volumes of lysis buffer and proteins were eluted with elution buffer (20mM Tris/HCl pH 7.9, 100 mM KCl, 250 mM imidazol). The proteins were treated with Ulp1 protease to remove the His-SUMO tag and dialyzed against the storage buffer (40 mM HEPES/KOH pH 7.6, 100 mM KCl, 5% glycerol). Subsequently, the protein mixture was subjected again to a Ni-IDA column and the ﬂow-through fraction containing tag-free DnaJ(1-105) or DnaJ(1-75) was collected.
Wild-type and mutant Hsc70 were produced recombinantly in E. coli BL21(DE3) pCODON+ as His6Smt3-fusion using expression plasmid pCA528-hsHSPA8 (Andre´ asson et al., 2008; Nguyen et al., 2017). Cell pellets were resuspended in lysis buffer (20 mM Tris/ HCl pH 7.9, 100 mM KCl, 1 mM PMSF), subjected to lysis by Microﬂuidizer Emulsi Flex C5 (Avestin, Ottawa, Canada), and afterward applied onto a column with Ni-IDA resin (Macherey-Nagel, Du€ren, Germany). The column was washed with 20 column volumes of the lysis buffer and 10 column volumes of the ATP-buffer (20 mM Tris/HCl pH 7.9, 100 mM KCl, 5 mM MgCl2, 5 mM ATP). Subsequently the proteins were eluted with elution buffer (20mM Tris/HCl pH 7.9, 100 mM KCl, 250 mM imidazol) and subjected to Ulp1 treatment to remove His-SUMO tag. The proteins were then dialyzed against the storage buffer (40 mM HEPES/KOH pH 7.6, 100 mM KCl, 5 mM MgCl2, 5% glycerol) and applied again onto Ni-IDA resin to yield a tag-free Hsc70 in the ﬂow-through fraction.
Hdj1 was production in E. coli WGK190 from the plasmid pUHE21-DNAJB1 (Ga€ssler et al., 2001) and puriﬁed using the same protocol as described above for E. coli DnaJ.
Protein crystallization, data collection and reﬁnement To stabilize the open conformation of the JD-DnaK-E47CDnaK-T199ADnaK-F529CDnaK fusion construct, the protein was oxidized in the presence of 5 mM ATP as described earlier (Kityk et al., 2012) and subsequently dialyzed against HKMG buffer (40 mM HEPES/KOH pH 7.6, 150 mM KCl, 5 mM MgCl2, 5% glycerol). To separate the intermolecular crosslinking products from intramolecular ones, the protein was subjected to size-exclusion chromatography on a Superdex 200 (GE Healthcare) in HNKM buffer (40 mM HEPES/NaOH pH 7.6, 80 mM NaCl, 20 mM KCl, 1 mM MgCl2). Afterward, the protein was concentrated to 18 mg/ml and subjected to crystallization.
JD-DnaKcryst was crystallized at 291 K with sitting drop vapor diffusion technique. The reservoir composition was 9% w/v PEG 8000, 0.1 M calcium acetate, and 0.1 M imidazole pH 6.5. Reservoir volume was 90 ml. The crystallization drop contained 200 nL protein solution mixed with 100 nL reservoir solution. Crystals were visible after 20 h and harvested and ﬂash frozen in liquid nitrogen after 3 days using 20% glycerol as cryo-protectant. Diffraction data were collected from one crystal at European Synchrotron Radiation Facility (ESRF) beamline ID23 at 100 K at a wavelength of 0.873 A˚ .
Structure determination and reﬁnement – Diffraction data was integrated using XDS (Kabsch, 2010) and merged and scaled using AIMLESS (Evans, 2006). Phases were obtained by molecular replacement with PHASER (McCoy et al., 2007) using the structure of full-length DnaK (PBD: 4B9Q; Kityk et al., 2012) as search model. The structural model was iteratively built in Coot (Emsley et al., 2010) alternating with cycles of reﬁnement in PHENIX (Afonine et al., 2012). The asymmetric unit contains one JD-DnaKcryst molecule. Molprobity (Chen et al., 2010) was used to assess the quality of the structure and indicated that 98.5% of residues were within favored Ramachandran regions. No residues were identiﬁed as Ramachandran outliers. The data collection and reﬁnement statistics are summarized in Table 1. Crystal contacts and the interface between DnaK and DnaJ were analyzed using PISA (Krissinel and Henrick, 2007). DnaJ (residues R19 and K23) is involved in only one small crystal contact of 100 A˚ 2 interface size with a DnaK molecule related by symmetry operation –X+1, Y+1, Z.
Single turn-over ATPase assay The ATPase activities of DnaKwt and DnaK mutant proteins were determined under single turnover conditions. The DnaK-ATP complexes (ﬁnal volume 50 mL) were formed by mixing DnaK (ﬁnal concentration 30 mM) and 2 mL of ATP-mix (20 mM ATP, 12 mCi [a32P]-ATP) in reaction buffer A (25 mM HEPES pH 7.6, 50 mM KCl 10 mM MgCl2 and leaving the mixture for 2 minutes on ice. The complex was isolated at 4C by gel ﬁltration on Sephadex G-50 (GE Healthcare) columns, pre-saturated with 1 mL of a BSA solution (1 mg/ml) and pre-equilibrated with 3 column volumes of buffer A. Twenty fractions (2 drops/fraction) were collected. The ﬁrst four fractions containing radioactivity as detected by a Geiger counter were pooled, divided into 6.5 mL aliquots, snap frozen in liquid nitrogen and kept at À80C. For the ATPase activity determination DnaK-ATP complexes were thawed in a water bath
e3 Molecular Cell 69, 227–237.e1–e4, January 18, 2018

at 30C and, after withdrawal of 0.5 mL for the 0 time point, mixed with 44 mL reaction buffer containing either no cofactors or 20-50 nM DnaJ (depending on the experiment) or 0.25 to 1 mM s32 or both. At different time points a 2 mL aliquot was spotted onto a PEI Cellulose TLC plate. Developing the plates in the TLC solution (400 mM LiCl, 10% acetic acid) separated ADP from ATP. Dried plates were exposed to FI-screens overnight and relative amounts of ATP and ADP were quantiﬁed by Fuji FLA 2000 Phosphoimager.
For JD-DnaK fusion protein and for DnaKwt in the presence of high concentration of DnaJ quenched-ﬂow instrument KinTek RQF-3 was used. DnaK (10 mM) was ﬁrst mixed with ATP (8 mM) than aged for 1 s and subsequently mixed with HKM buffer without proteins or including DnaJ (10 mM) at room temperature. At preset time points the reaction was quenched by diluting the mixture with 3 volumes of TLC solution. 2 mL of the quenched reaction were spotted onto a PEI Cellulose TLC plate, with subsequent nucleotides separation as described above.
Luciferase refolding assay Fireﬂy luciferase (10 mM) was denatured in unfolding buffer (30 mM Tris/acetate pH 7.5, 6 M guanidinium$HCl) for 10 min at 30C and subsequently diluted 125-fold (ﬁnal concentration 80 nM) into refolding buffer (25 mM HEPES/KOH pH 7.6, 100 mM KAc, 10 mM MgAc2, 2 mM ATP, 5 mM DTT), containing DnaK (800 nM), DnaJ (40 nM) and GrpE (400 nM) at 30C. At different time points 1 mL of the reaction mixture was diluted into 124 mL of assay buffer (100 mM KxHyPO4 pH 7.6, 25 mM glycyl-glycine, 100 mM KAc, 15 mM MgAc2, 5 mM ATP) and subsequently mixed with 125 mL of luciferin (160 mM) in a Biolumat (Berthold). Upon mixing chemical luminescence was measured for 5 s.
In vivo complementation assay E. coli BB1994 (DdnaK strain) or E. coli WKG 190 (DdnaJ DcbpA strain) were transformed with plasmids containing IPTG-inducible dnaK alleles or L-arabinose-inducible dnaJ alleles, respectively, which harbored the mutations of interest. Tenfold serial dilutions of a 100-fold diluted overnight culture were spotted (10 mL) onto LB-agar plates, containing 50 mM IPTG or 6.6 mM L-arabinose, and appropriate antibiotics. Plates were incubated overnight at 30C and 40C. Protein expression levels at 40C were veriﬁed by immune blotting using a DnaK-speciﬁc Rabbit antiserum 47119 received from B. Bukau.
Substrate afﬁnity determination The dissociation equilibrium constants for the DnaK-substrate complexes were determined by ﬂuorescence intensity measurements. IAANS-labeled s32-Q132-Q144-C peptide (100 nM) was mixed in HKM buffer (25 mM HEPES/KOH pH 7.6, 150 mM KCl, 5 mM MgCl2) and incubated with increasing concentrations of DnaKwt or DnaK-D477A (in the range of 0.6 nM – 10 mM) at 30C for at least 30 min. Subsequently, the ﬂuorescence intensity was measured on a ClarioStar plate reader (excitation ﬁlter: 360-20; emission ﬁlter: 450-10). In order to calculate KD values the obtained results were ﬁtted by the quadratic solution of the law of mass action. QUANTIFICATION AND STATISTICAL ANALYSIS
All biochemical assays were performed at least 3 times independently. Data were analyzed with GraphPad Prism 6.0 (GraphPad Software). Statistical signiﬁcance was estimated by ANOVA tests as indicated in ﬁgure legends.
